{"valid":true,"title":"TokenSharingService Exported Without android:permission — Signature Check Is the Only Defense Against Unauthorized Token Access","summary":"The `TokenSharingService` in Microsoft Teams for Android is declared in `AndroidManifest.xml` with `android:exported="true"` and **no `android:permission` attribute**. This means any installed Android application can call `bindService()` to obtain an `IBinder` handle to `TokenProviderBinder` — the OS will not enforce any permission gate before allowing the bind.

The sole runtime defense is `isCallerAllowed()` in `TokenSharingService.java`, which:
1. Retrieves the caller's package name(s) via `Binder.getCallingUid()`
2. Computes the SHA-256 fingerprint of the caller's signing certificate
3. Compares it against a hardcoded/remotely-fetched allowlist of Microsoft certificate fingerprints (`tokenshare_signatures` array: OneDrive, Word/Excel/PowerPoint/Outlook/Lync/Defender, Skype)

This check is **application-layer only** — it runs inside `internalGetAccounts()` and `internalGetToken()` after `onMAMBind()` already returns the binder to the caller. An attacker app with a non-Microsoft signing certificate will get `isCallerAllowed()` returning `false`, meaning `internalGetToken` returns `null` and `internalGetAccounts` returns an empty list. A second bypass path (`mIsDebugMode`) is only set to `true` when `AppBuildConfigurationHelper.isDebug() && AppBuildConfigurationHelper.isDev()` — a build-time flag that is `false` in production releases.

The signature verification itself relies on `PackageManager.getPackageInfo()` with `GET_SIGNATURES` flag, which on Android < 9 (API 28) is vulnerable to the "Package Signature Spoofing" attack if the device is rooted or uses a custom firmware. On modern Android (≥ API 28), `GET_SIGNING_CERTIFICATES` mitigates this. However, the code uses the legacy `GET_SIGNATURES` flag (value `64`), not `GET_SIGNING_CERTIFICATES` (value `0x8000000`). This means on devices running Android < 9, a malicious app could present a certificate chain that includes a trusted Microsoft certificate as a parent, causing `isPackageHaveValidSignature()` to return `true` for a non-Microsoft app.

