## Vulnerability Report

**AdBlock Detection Exploitable via Pre-Existing `.adsbox` DOM Element — False Negative / Active Manipulation**

**File:** `fingerprintjs2/fingerprint2.js`, lines 843–857 (`getAdBlock`)

**Vulnerability:**
```js
getAdBlock: function(){
  var ads = document.createElement("div");
  ads.innerHTML = "&nbsp;";
  ads.className = "adsbox";
  var result = false;
  try {
    document.body.appendChild(ads);
    result = document.getElementsByClassName("adsbox")[0].offsetHeight === 0;  // ← BUG
    document.body.removeChild(ads);
  } catch (e) {
    result = false;
  }
  return result;
},
```

**The Bug:**
`document.getElementsByClassName("adsbox")[0]` selects the **first** element with class `adsbox` in the DOM — **not** the element that was just appended. If the page already contains any element with class `adsbox` that is visible (has a non-zero height), then even when an ad blocker hides newly-inserted `.adsbox` elements, this check returns `false` (reports no ad blocker), producing a false negative.

**Active Exploitation:**
A page that wants to conceal its ad-block detection from the fingerprint result can simply insert a permanent visible element with class `adsbox` before FingerprintJS2 is invoked:
```js
// Before loading FingerprintJS2:
var decoy = document.createElement("div");
decoy.className = "adsbox";
decoy.style.height = "1px";
document.body.appendChild(decoy);
// Now getAdBlock() will always return false (not adblocked)
// even for users who ARE running an ad blocker
```

**Converse Attack (forced false positive):**
Any script on the page (XSS, third-party script, same-page attacker) can add a hidden `.adsbox` element ahead of the library's check with `offsetHeight === 0`, making the library incorrectly report that ALL users are adblocking:
```js
var trick = document.createElement("div");
trick.className = "adsbox";
trick.style.display = "none"; // height = 0
document.body.insertBefore(trick, document.body.firstChild);
```

**Impact:**
Any downstream anti-fraud or analytics system that relies on the `adblock` fingerprint component can be systematically deceived to produce incorrect results, either to hide ad blocker usage or to falsely flag all users as ad-blocking.

## Related Files

- `fingerprintjs2/fingerprint2.js`

