{"valid":false,"title":"AdBlock Detection False Negative via Pre-existing `.adsbox` DOM Element — Logic Bug, Not a Security Vulnerability","summary":"The `getAdBlock()` function in `fingerprintjs2/fingerprint2.js` (lines 844–857) uses `document.getElementsByClassName("adsbox")[0]` to check if an ad blocker is active. Since this selects the **first** element with class `adsbox` in the DOM rather than the specifically-created element, a pre-existing visible `.adsbox` element on the page could cause the function to return `false` even when an ad blocker is hiding the newly appended element.

This is a **client-side logic flaw in a browser fingerprinting library**, not a remotely exploitable security vulnerability. The "attack" described requires JavaScript code to already be executing in the same page context as FingerprintJS2 — meaning the attacker already has full DOM access. Any attacker with the ability to inject or run JavaScript on the page can trivially manipulate any fingerprint component, not just this one. The scenario described (inserting a `.adsbox` decoy element) requires either XSS (a separate, more severe vulnerability) or a rogue same-origin third-party script.

FingerprintJS2 is a client-side fingerprinting library that explicitly acknowledges an error margin and is not designed for security-critical trust decisions. Its fingerprint values are inherently client-controllable. Manipulating the `adblock` component value does not grant any access, escalate privileges, expose sensitive data, or have any server-side security impact. This is a known design limitation of client-side fingerprinting — not a remotely exploitable security vulnerability — and does not meet the bar for a valid security finding.","proofOfConcept":"To confirm this is a logic bug and not a remotely exploitable vulnerability:

