{"valid":true,"title":"CallNotificationSettingsProvider Broken Access Control: Any App Can Access User Identity Data via Normal-Level Permission","summary":"## Broken Allowlist Check in Exported ContentProvider Exposes User Identity Data

The `CallNotificationSettingsProvider` class at `teams_java/sources/com/microsoft/skype/teams/data/providers/CallNotificationSettingsProvider.java` is an exported Android ContentProvider (declared with `android:exported="true"`) that is intended to expose call notification settings only to specific Microsoft apps. The provider is protected by a custom permission `com.microsoft.teams.data.providers.callnotification.readPermission` declared at `android:protectionLevel="normal"` — meaning any third-party app can obtain it automatically without user interaction.

## Attack Path

The code at lines 91–95 contains a for-loop intended to enforce an in-app allowlist (`ALLOWED_APP_PACKAGES`) against calling app packages, but the `if` body is **completely empty** — it performs no action (no `return`, no `break`, no flag setting). After the loop completes for any calling package, execution falls through unconditionally to data retrieval. A malicious app can:

